MGARCH

Vitalii Rudko

June, 2020

Abstract

This project is extension of the previous one on the VAR model. The first objective of this project is to build and test one of the MGARCH models in R. For that purpose the DCC model was selected. The second objective is to learn how to interpret the particular results at every stage. The last objective is to determine whether there is any relationship between S&P500 daily returns and returns of two big tech companies, namely Microsoft and Apple. Note, the last project on VAR model was built using monthly returns, it was changed for daily, because there was a weak dependence between variables.
  • 1 Preparing time series for analysis
  • 2 Preliminary analysis of the data
  • 3 VAR model selection and checking
  • 4 Exponentially weighted estimate
  • 5 The DCC model
  • 6 Results of forecasting
  • 7 Conclusions
  • References

1 Preparing time series for analysis

I am starting with uploading necessary packages. Notice the package yahooquotes is a custom package for importing and exporting data. The package vars serves for the model building and testing. Package MTS was used for estimating multivariate Ljung-Box statistics. aTSA enabled to conduct ADF tests. Package forecast improves a little bit existing functions, acf, pcf and ccf. Package roll adds the functions for estimation of rolling statistics. Packages rugarch and rmgarch developed for building univariate and multivariate GARCH models respectively. The last package ggplot2 is a popular tool for visualization of data.

# Importing packages.
library(yahooquotes) 
# Custom package

library(roll)
#Documentation: https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/roll/roll.pdf

library(vars)

# Importing data. 
tickers <-c("^GSPC","MSFT","AAPL")

data <- yahoo_quotes(tickers, 
                     origin = '2010-01-01',
                     today = "2020-01-02"
                     )

names(data) <- c("Date","SP500","MSFT","AAPL")

#Full names: 
#SP500 - S&P500
#MSFT - Microsoft Inc. 
#AAPL - Apple Inc.

Since we are working with the daily data, we can use log returns without fear of loosing accuracy.

# Calculating returns.
data$r_SP500 <- c(NA, diff(log(data$SP500)) )
data$r_MSFT <- c(NA, diff(log(data$MSFT)) )
data$r_AAPL <- c(NA, diff(log(data$AAPL)) )
#Creating time series. 
SP500 <- ts(data$r_SP500[-1],
            start = 2010, 
            end = 2020, 
            frequency = 365)

MSFT <-  ts(data$r_MSFT[-1],
            start = 2010, 
            end = 2020, 
            frequency = 365)

AAPL <-  ts(data$r_AAPL[-1],
            start = 2010, 
            end = 2020, 
            frequency = 365)

whole <- cbind(SP500, MSFT, AAPL)

3 VAR model selection and checking

The vars package helps to choose the appropriate specification of a model by checking four criteria, namely AIC, HQ, SC(BIC) and FPE. AIC criterion tends to choose models with higher order, comparing to HQ and SC. The simpler model is preferred, thus we choose the order of 1.

info_whole <- VARselect(whole, lag.max = 20, type = "const") 
info_whole$selection
## AIC(n)  HQ(n)  SC(n) FPE(n) 
##     19      1      1     19

Now, we can build the model. The sum of the characteristic roots is less than 1, so the process is stationary. Unfortunately, not all parameters are statistically significant, the fit is still not good and residuals are correlated. This also means, that the poorly fitted mean model may lead to a low forecasting capacity of the MGARCH model. The correlation of the residuals is studied broader in the following steps.

#Building the VAR(1) model. 
VAR_1 <- vars::VAR(whole, p = 1, type = "const", season = NULL, exog = NULL)

4 Exponentially weighted estimate

The exponentially weighted moving-average (EWMA) method can be applied for constracting a smooth covariance matrix, which can be used, according to Tsay (2016), as a banchmark for our future model. Since I did not find any package that would provide that type of function, I had to use a code provided as an appendix for one of the textbooks by Ruppert and Matteson (2015), the source is given inside the code. The first function estimates lambda, and the last one estimates the covariance matrix. In the two subsequent chunks those estimations are performed using innovations from the VAR(1) model and calculated lambda. Note, the function is hidden, in order to see the source code please visit the web page provided.

#SOURCE: "Additional R functions for: Statistics and Data Analysis for Financial 
#         Engineering, 2nd Edition" by Ruppert and Matteson. 
#         Link: https://people.orie.cornell.edu/davidr/SDAFE2/Rscripts/SDAFE2.R

# Estimating lambda for EWMA function. 
VAR_1.lambda <- est.ewma(lambda.0 = 0.95, innov = VAR_1.res)
# Estimating EWMA.
VAR_1.sigma  <- sigma.ewma(lambda = VAR_1.lambda$lambda.hat, innov = VAR_1.res)

5 The DCC model

According to Caporin and Michael McAleer (2013), DCC model does not yield conditional correlations directly, therefore it must be treated with a greater caution. According to the same source its properties poorly described, and basically the model is not derived, but rather stated. Also, it is assumed that all the conditional correlations have the same dynamics. In general, the author suggests to use DCC as a filter not as a model. However, in this study, I will assume, that DCC can be used as a model, and that it is able to produce sensible results .

The model is based on the decomposition of the conditional variance matrix, and the variances are allowed to estimated separetly. It means, we can use different specifications of the univariate GARCH models. Since we have correlated standard errors it is justified to use q order greater than zero, so I choose a standard (1,1) GARCH model. Its mean follows ARMA(1,0) process, since our VAR model is of the first order. That specifications are chosen for all three assets.

The report of estimated DCC is presented below. It shows that all parameters are significantly different from zero. The sum of alpha and beta is less than 1 in every case, thus the model is stationary.

# Estimating DCC model. 
garch11.spec <- ugarchspec(mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(1,0)), 
                          variance.model = list(garchOrder = c(1,1), 
                          model = "sGARCH"), 
                          distribution.model = "std")

dcc.garch11.spec <- dccspec(uspec = multispec( replicate(3, garch11.spec) ),
                           VAR = TRUE,
                           lag.max = 1,
                           lag.criterion = "HQ",
                           dccOrder = c(1,1), 
                           distribution = "mvt")


dcc.fit <- dccfit(dcc.garch11.spec, data = whole)
dcc.fit
## 
## *---------------------------------*
## *          DCC GARCH Fit          *

The rolling standard deviations and correlations will serve as the second benchmark for our model. The results in Figure 5.1 and Figure 5.2 generally show the good fit.

7 Conclusions

The following conclusions can be drawn from the study:

  1. Apple is more volatile than Microsoft, which makes it the riskier investment.
  2. The companies and the index are cross-correlated on average in around 50% of cases.
  3. The forecasting capacity of a MGARCH model relies on the goodness-of-fit of the assumed mean model. It is possible to compensate the bad fit by choosing appropriate \(q\) and \(\beta\) orders for GARCH models and the DCC model respectively.
  4. Even if the model seems to be well fitted, it is still should be treated with a great caution in terms of forecasting, as in practice some of underlying assumptions may not be fulfilled.
  5. As an alternative, the BEKK model should be considered for derivation of conditional correlations, as it is more consistent according to Caporin and Michael McAleer (2013).

References

Caporin, Massimiliano, and Michael McAleer. 2013. Ten Things You Should Know About the Dynamic Conditional Correlation Representation. Econometrics 1 (1): 11526. https://doi.org/10.3390/econometrics1010115.

Ruppert, David, and David S. Matteson. 2015. Statistics and Data Analysis for Financial Engineering. Springer Texts in Statistics. New York, NY: Springer New York. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4939-2614-5.

Tsay, Ruey S. 2016. Analysis of Financial Time Series. Wiley Series in Probability and Statistics. Sahibabad, In: Wiley India. https://doi.org/10.1002/9780470644560.
